00:04:15.710 --> 00:04:17.810
And money flooded
into neuroscience.

00:04:17.810 --> 00:04:20.709
And most it was spent on
neuroimaging technology.

00:04:20.709 --> 00:04:23.260
So we got really, really good
at peering inside the brain

00:04:23.260 --> 00:04:24.930
and figuring out
what's going on.

00:04:24.930 --> 00:04:27.280
So for the very first
time in history,

00:04:27.280 --> 00:04:30.900
we actually are now starting
to decode what happens in flow.

00:04:30.900 --> 00:04:33.690
And I'll just give you a
little bit of the neuroscience,

00:04:33.690 --> 00:04:35.250
just so you have some context.

00:04:35.250 --> 00:04:37.560
Two main things are important.

00:04:37.560 --> 00:04:42.379
From a neuroanatomical level,
normally the old idea of what

00:04:42.379 --> 00:04:44.420
happened about ultimate
performance--and I'm sure

00:04:44.420 --> 00:04:46.690
you're all familiar with
it-- the 10% brain myth,

00:04:46.690 --> 00:04:48.750
the idea that we're only
using 10% of our brain.

00:04:48.750 --> 00:04:50.840
So ultimate
performance, aka flow,

00:04:50.840 --> 00:04:53.260
must be the full
brain on overdrive.

00:04:53.260 --> 00:04:56.230
Turns out we had it
exactly backwards.

00:04:56.230 --> 00:04:59.252
In flow, parts of the brain
are not becoming hyperactive.

00:04:59.252 --> 00:05:00.502
They're actually deactivating.

00:05:00.502 --> 00:05:01.990
They're shutting down.

00:05:01.990 --> 00:05:05.180
The technical term for this is
transient-- meaning temporary--

00:05:05.180 --> 00:05:07.930
hypo, H-Y-P-O, it's
the opposite of hyper,

00:05:07.930 --> 00:05:10.490
it means to slow down, to
shut down, to deactivate--

00:05:10.490 --> 00:05:12.890
frontality, which refers
to the prefrontal cortex,

00:05:12.890 --> 00:05:14.870
the part of your brain
that's right back here.

00:05:14.870 --> 00:05:17.317
Prefrontal cortex is
your executive function.

00:05:17.317 --> 00:05:19.150
It's all of your higher
cognitive functions.

00:05:19.150 --> 00:05:21.750
It's the part that you
most associate with you,

00:05:21.750 --> 00:05:23.920
so your sense of morality,
your sense of will,

00:05:23.920 --> 00:05:26.900
your sense of self,
complex decision making.

00:05:26.900 --> 00:05:29.830
In flow, that portion
of the brain shuts down.

00:05:29.830 --> 00:05:32.460
So why does time pass
so strangely in flow?

00:05:32.460 --> 00:05:34.770
Because time, it turns
out, is calculated

00:05:34.770 --> 00:05:36.510
all over the prefrontal cortex.

00:05:36.510 --> 00:05:38.760
And as parts of it
start to wink out,

00:05:38.760 --> 00:05:42.280
we can no longer separate past,
from present, from future.

00:05:42.280 --> 00:05:44.862
We're plunged into what's
called the deep now.

00:05:44.862 --> 00:05:47.070
Another thing that happens
in the prefrontal cortex--

00:05:47.070 --> 00:05:48.685
and this is probably
the best part--

00:05:48.685 --> 00:05:50.960
is when the dorsal lateral
prefrontal cortex-- and there's

00:05:50.960 --> 00:05:52.001
going to be a quiz later.

00:05:52.001 --> 00:05:54.000
So I hope you're
all taking notes.

00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:56.020
When this portion of
your brain shuts down,

00:05:56.020 --> 00:05:57.020
it does a lot of things.

00:05:57.020 --> 00:05:58.450
But one of the most
important things it does,

00:05:58.450 --> 00:05:59.760
is it's your inner critic.

00:05:59.760 --> 00:06:02.042
So that nagging,
always-on, defeatist voice

00:06:02.042 --> 00:06:03.750
that's in your head
that doesn't shut up,

00:06:03.750 --> 00:06:06.470
that won't leave you
alone, shuts up in flow.

00:06:06.470 --> 00:06:08.720
So we experience this
profound liberation.

00:06:08.720 --> 00:06:11.520
We are literally free of
ourselves for the first time.

00:06:11.520 --> 00:06:14.370
As a result, creativity
goes up, risk-taking

00:06:14.370 --> 00:06:16.500
goes up, et cetera, et cetera.

00:06:16.500 --> 00:06:18.810
There's also a
combination of five

00:06:18.810 --> 00:06:20.470
of the most potent
neurochemicals

00:06:20.470 --> 00:06:21.810
the brain can produce.

00:06:21.810 --> 00:06:23.300
These are all
performance-enhancing

00:06:23.300 --> 00:06:23.799
chemicals.

00:06:23.799 --> 00:06:25.420
But they serve a
second function,

00:06:25.420 --> 00:06:27.986
which is they're all
feel-good, pleasure drugs.

00:06:27.986 --> 00:06:29.360
And just to give
you an idea, one

00:06:29.360 --> 00:06:30.943
of the chemicals
that shows up in flow

00:06:30.943 --> 00:06:33.090
is dopamine, which you guys
have probably heard of.

00:06:33.090 --> 00:06:34.830
Dopamine-- well, let's back up.

00:06:34.830 --> 00:06:38.602
Cocaine is widely considered the
most addictive drug on Earth.

00:06:38.602 --> 00:06:41.060
All that happens when somebody
uses cocaine, is the brain--

00:06:41.060 --> 00:06:41.600
JASON SILVA: They get dopamine.

00:06:41.600 --> 00:06:43.040
STEVEN KOTLER:
They get dopamine.

00:06:43.040 --> 00:06:44.450
So you get dopamine.

00:06:44.450 --> 00:06:45.390
You get endorphins.

00:06:45.390 --> 00:06:48.390
And just endorphins are
opiates, natural version

00:06:48.390 --> 00:06:51.130
of heroin or morphine,
just the one our brain

00:06:51.130 --> 00:06:52.610
produces as painkillers.

00:06:52.610 --> 00:06:54.370
But the most common
endorphin in the brain

00:06:54.370 --> 00:06:57.660
is 100 times more powerful
than medical morphine.

00:06:57.660 --> 00:06:59.130
The combination--
so first of all,

00:06:59.130 --> 00:07:00.870
if you wanted to go out
onto the street and cocktail

00:07:00.870 --> 00:07:02.790
the street drug
versions of this state,

00:07:02.790 --> 00:07:04.460
you'd end up dead or in a coma.

00:07:04.460 --> 00:07:05.189
Would not work.

00:07:05.189 --> 00:07:07.480
Some of the drugs would
actually cancel themselves out.

00:07:07.480 --> 00:07:08.940
Your brain does it perfectly.

00:07:08.940 --> 00:07:12.280
Which means flow is the most
addictive state on Earth.

00:07:12.280 --> 00:07:14.814
We will go extraordinarily
far out of our way

00:07:14.814 --> 00:07:16.980
to get more of it-- as
Jason, I'm sure, will attest.

00:07:16.980 --> 00:07:17.890
JASON SILVA: Yeah.

00:07:17.890 --> 00:07:18.960
Well, one of the
things that's blown

00:07:18.960 --> 00:07:21.490
my mind about the attention
that flow has gotten recently

00:07:21.490 --> 00:07:25.270
in the media is that
it's given it a language.

00:07:25.270 --> 00:07:29.910
It's given us an ability to
describe the ineffable ecstasy

00:07:29.910 --> 00:07:33.670
of being in that zone,
being in that pocket--

00:07:33.670 --> 00:07:36.780
whether it's the jazz musician
when he is improvising

00:07:36.780 --> 00:07:39.660
and he literally transcends
himself, the basketball player

00:07:39.660 --> 00:07:41.410
achieving the impossible,
the snowboarder,

00:07:41.410 --> 00:07:44.540
the elite athletes pushing
beyond the limits of the sport.

00:07:44.540 --> 00:07:46.560
Something is happening
in this moment.

00:07:46.560 --> 00:07:48.750
And I remember there was
some science recently

00:07:48.750 --> 00:07:51.480
where they scanned
the brains of rappers.

00:07:51.480 --> 00:07:53.660
And they had them
freestyle lyrics, which

00:07:53.660 --> 00:07:55.702
means completely improvised.

00:07:55.702 --> 00:07:58.160
And then, of course, they had
them recite memorized lyrics.

00:07:58.160 --> 00:07:59.618
And what they said
is exactly that.

00:07:59.618 --> 00:08:01.790
The lateral prefrontal
cortex, the inner critic,

00:08:01.790 --> 00:08:03.640
the self-editing, goes away.

00:08:03.640 --> 00:08:07.240
Or as your partner, Jamie Wheal,
says, your inner Woody Allen.

00:08:07.240 --> 00:08:11.050
That self-crippling self-doubt,
that self-consciousness,

00:08:11.050 --> 00:08:14.210
that so often acts
as paralysis for us--

00:08:14.210 --> 00:08:17.240
to be free from that
is such ecstasy.

00:08:17.240 --> 00:08:21.630
And so what I'm curious about
is how do you take this and make

00:08:21.630 --> 00:08:22.460
this mainstream?

00:08:22.460 --> 00:08:26.851
Because yes, it is all about
us getting high and entering

00:08:26.851 --> 00:08:27.600
these flow states.

00:08:27.600 --> 00:08:29.070
But then what do we do
with these flow states,

00:08:29.070 --> 00:08:30.260
when we say we achieve
the impossible?

00:08:30.260 --> 00:08:32.010
You give a lot lectures,
corporate talks

00:08:32.010 --> 00:08:34.130
all over the world because
apparently people doing

00:08:34.130 --> 00:08:36.190
business are 10 times
more productive when

00:08:36.190 --> 00:08:37.130
they achieve flow.

00:08:37.130 --> 00:08:40.460
So it's like, can you grab this
high that artists are using,

00:08:40.460 --> 00:08:42.940
that athletes are using, and
bring it into the workplace,

00:08:42.940 --> 00:08:45.070
and bring it into
these new spaces

00:08:45.070 --> 00:08:47.184
so that we can essentially
upgrade society.

00:08:47.184 --> 00:08:48.600
I mean, this is
an ambitious idea,

00:08:48.600 --> 00:08:51.020
but this is what you guys are
doing at Flow Genome, right?

00:08:51.020 --> 00:08:52.310
STEVEN KOTLER: It is
kind of what we're doing.

00:08:52.310 --> 00:08:55.240
And they're not 10 times-- so
McKinsey did a 10-year study.

00:08:55.240 --> 00:08:57.820
And they found top
executives in flow

00:08:57.820 --> 00:08:59.320
are five times more productive.

00:08:59.320 --> 00:09:01.130
So it's 500% more productive.

00:09:01.130 --> 00:09:03.670
It means you could
go to work on Monday,

00:09:03.670 --> 00:09:05.810
spend Monday in a flow
state, take Tuesday

00:09:05.810 --> 00:09:07.570
through Friday off,
and get as much done

00:09:07.570 --> 00:09:08.930
as your steady-state peers.

00:09:08.930 --> 00:09:11.190
That's how much of an
amplification in performance

00:09:11.190 --> 00:09:13.280
you're actually talking about.

00:09:13.280 --> 00:09:16.810
What we now know is--
and it's interesting.

00:09:16.810 --> 00:09:19.971
So for a really long
time, studying flow

00:09:19.971 --> 00:09:22.095
was problematic because
how do you know if somebody

00:09:22.095 --> 00:09:22.550
was in a flow state?

00:09:22.550 --> 00:09:24.910
You had to give them a
subjective questionnaire.

00:09:24.910 --> 00:09:26.480
And it's flimsy science.

00:09:26.480 --> 00:09:29.490
And it's extremely
well-validated questionnaire.

00:09:29.490 --> 00:09:31.240
There's about 50 years'
worth of research.

00:09:31.240 --> 00:09:34.730
But what started happening
in the past 25 years

00:09:34.730 --> 00:09:37.500
is, for reasons I'll get to in
a second, action adventure sport

00:09:37.500 --> 00:09:39.800
athletes-- snowboarders,
skiers, surfers,

00:09:39.800 --> 00:09:42.980
whatnot-- they got
better at reliably

00:09:42.980 --> 00:09:45.895
and repeatedly reproducing
the state of flow than anybody

00:09:45.895 --> 00:09:47.770
else pretty much in the
history of the world.

00:09:47.770 --> 00:09:50.815
As a result, we've seen
near-exponential growth

00:09:50.815 --> 00:09:53.190
in ultimate human performance
in action adventure sports.

00:09:53.190 --> 00:09:55.530
So incredible things have
happened in the past 25 years.

00:09:55.530 --> 00:09:58.260
More impossible feats had
been done than ever before.

00:09:58.260 --> 00:10:00.380
From a research
perspective, they gave us

00:10:00.380 --> 00:10:02.210
something we've never
had before, which

00:10:02.210 --> 00:10:04.470
is at the upper
level of competition,

00:10:04.470 --> 00:10:06.590
these men and women
are performing at--

00:10:06.590 --> 00:10:09.150
if they're not in flow, they're
going home in a body bag.

00:10:09.150 --> 00:10:10.730
Or they're going
to the hospital.

00:10:10.730 --> 00:10:13.330
So suddenly, our
research subjects,

00:10:13.330 --> 00:10:15.030
if they lived through
the experience,

00:10:15.030 --> 00:10:16.570
we knew they were in flow.

00:10:16.570 --> 00:10:21.480
And having this as a backdrop,
a data set to work with,

00:10:21.480 --> 00:10:23.010
has allowed us to
work backwards.

00:10:23.010 --> 00:10:27.320
We now know there are 17
triggers, 17 pre-conditions

00:10:27.320 --> 00:10:28.410
that lead to more flow.

00:10:28.410 --> 00:10:30.493
And we also know there's
something called the flow

00:10:30.493 --> 00:10:33.550
cycle, a four-stage process
the state moves through,

00:10:33.550 --> 00:10:35.650
which is sort of the
map of the territory.

00:10:35.650 --> 00:10:37.941
You combine these things,
like we do at the Flow Genome

00:10:37.941 --> 00:10:39.794
Project-- and this
isn't, I mean there's

00:10:39.794 --> 00:10:41.210
lots of different
people out there

00:10:41.210 --> 00:10:42.500
teaching flow and whatnot.

00:10:42.500 --> 00:10:44.587
But I'll just give
you our numbers.

00:10:44.587 --> 00:10:46.670
We've taught-- I don't
even know how many people--

00:10:46.670 --> 00:10:48.430
thousands of people
at this point.

00:10:48.430 --> 00:10:50.524
On average, when people
come through our courses--

00:10:50.524 --> 00:10:52.690
six-week course, by the
way, not even a hard course.

00:10:52.690 --> 00:10:54.023
The homework's a little strange.

00:10:54.023 --> 00:10:56.320
But it's a six-week course.

00:10:56.320 --> 00:10:59.990
People are reporting a fivefold,
so a 500%, increase in flow,

00:10:59.990 --> 00:11:03.470
a 500% increase in creativity,
and a 300% increase

00:11:03.470 --> 00:11:04.720
in self-confidence.

00:11:04.720 --> 00:11:06.989
And the last one, by the
way, self-confidence--

00:11:06.989 --> 00:11:08.780
we had no idea that it
was going to happen.

00:11:08.780 --> 00:11:10.905
It was just something that
emerged out of the data.

00:11:10.905 --> 00:11:12.810
We were really shocked by it.

00:11:12.810 --> 00:11:15.680
But yes, the state is
entirely trainable.

00:11:15.680 --> 00:11:18.420
And as we get better
at our neuroscience,

00:11:18.420 --> 00:11:20.170
it's going to get more
and more trainable.

00:11:20.170 --> 00:11:21.290
JASON SILVA: So eventually
we'll get to the point

00:11:21.290 --> 00:11:23.248
that we can literally be
able to press a button

00:11:23.248 --> 00:11:25.650
and get into our highest
state, so to speak.

00:11:25.650 --> 00:11:27.191
STEVEN KOTLER: You
can do it already.

00:11:27.191 --> 00:11:29.600
I mean, so one of the ways
they induce flow artificially

00:11:29.600 --> 00:11:31.380
now is transcranial
magnetic stimulation.

00:11:31.380 --> 00:11:33.880
They literally shoot a
big neuromagnetic pulse

00:11:33.880 --> 00:11:34.840
through the brain.

00:11:34.840 --> 00:11:36.440
They knock out the
prefrontal cortex,

00:11:36.440 --> 00:11:38.980
inducing artificial flow,
kicking people into flow.

00:11:38.980 --> 00:11:40.160
DARPA did this.

00:11:40.160 --> 00:11:44.550
They took a group of snipers
and they trained them up in flow

00:11:44.550 --> 00:11:46.430
by knocking out the
prefrontal cortex.

00:11:46.430 --> 00:11:49.980
They found they learned 200%
to 500% faster than normal.

00:11:49.980 --> 00:11:54.820
They redid the study with
novice, nonmilitary archers,

00:11:54.820 --> 00:11:58.300
riflemen, and pistol shooters--
three different categories.

00:11:58.300 --> 00:12:00.740
They found the time it takes
to go from novice to expert

00:12:00.740 --> 00:12:02.780
can be cut in half by flow.

00:12:02.780 --> 00:12:04.857
So yes, there is
already a button for it.

00:12:04.857 --> 00:12:06.190
JASON SILVA: Which is wonderful.

00:12:06.190 --> 00:12:09.000
So besides it
being a wonderfully

00:12:09.000 --> 00:12:12.690
smart and productive technique
to assimilate and to learn,

00:12:12.690 --> 00:12:14.700
there's also its
connection fundamentally

00:12:14.700 --> 00:12:16.880
to the human condition.

00:12:16.880 --> 00:12:18.990
Jamie Wheal had a
wonderful TEDx Talk

00:12:18.990 --> 00:12:21.730
called-- your partner--
from "Altered States

00:12:21.730 --> 00:12:25.590
to Altered Traits" and this
idea of hacking the flow state.

00:12:25.590 --> 00:12:28.530
He said most of us, while we
recognize these flow states,

00:12:28.530 --> 00:12:32.910
we get hooked on the state
instead of raising the stage.

00:12:32.910 --> 00:12:34.260
So we go there.

00:12:34.260 --> 00:12:37.310
But then when we come back into
ourselves Monday morning again

00:12:37.310 --> 00:12:38.810
and it's like, what
the fuck, right?

00:12:38.810 --> 00:12:39.130
STEVEN KOTLER: Right.

00:12:39.130 --> 00:12:40.900
JASON SILVA: And part of the
thing that he was talking about

00:12:40.900 --> 00:12:42.710
is that if you think
of our self systems,

00:12:42.710 --> 00:12:44.590
the way that our
homeostasis right now,

00:12:44.590 --> 00:12:46.050
we're like a colander.

00:12:46.050 --> 00:12:47.440
And we're full of holes.

00:12:47.440 --> 00:12:50.251
And no matter how much flow
we pour in, we're draining.

00:12:50.251 --> 00:12:52.000
So you have to be
constantly pouring it in

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:53.530
to achieve any kind
of equilibrium.

00:12:53.530 --> 00:12:56.190
But then he talks about the
idea of turning our colander

00:12:56.190 --> 00:13:00.420
into a chalice so that we could
literally make flow the default

00:13:00.420 --> 00:13:01.340
condition.

00:13:01.340 --> 00:13:03.820
Now, technology is
advancing exponentially.

00:13:03.820 --> 00:13:06.030
We have new construction
kits for our reality.

00:13:06.030 --> 00:13:09.270
You explore this in abundance
in "Bold" and your new book

00:13:09.270 --> 00:13:10.640
"Tomorrowland."

00:13:10.640 --> 00:13:15.180
Can you speculate about how
we might raise the stage,

00:13:15.180 --> 00:13:19.557
reverse-engineer ourselves,
creating a default flow state?

00:13:19.557 --> 00:13:21.390
STEVEN KOTLER: It's an
interesting question.

00:13:21.390 --> 00:13:24.670
One thing for sure, there's no
such thing as a permanent flow

00:13:24.670 --> 00:13:25.660
state.

00:13:25.660 --> 00:13:27.975
JASON SILVA: Bummer.

00:13:27.975 --> 00:13:29.350
STEVEN KOTLER:
The neurochemicals

00:13:29.350 --> 00:13:31.700
that produce flow
are in short supply.

00:13:31.700 --> 00:13:33.630
So once you burn
through them, and you

00:13:33.630 --> 00:13:36.030
can burn through some
of them in 20-- dopamine

00:13:36.030 --> 00:13:37.946
and norepinephrine will
burn out of your brain

00:13:37.946 --> 00:13:38.880
in about 20 minutes.

00:13:38.880 --> 00:13:40.510
Takes a little while
to replenish them.

00:13:40.510 --> 00:13:42.934
So there's no--
occasionally people

00:13:42.934 --> 00:13:45.350
will come up to me like, I
live in a permanent flow state.

00:13:45.350 --> 00:13:46.250
And I'm like, yeah.

00:13:46.250 --> 00:13:47.249
We have a word for that.

00:13:47.249 --> 00:13:48.980
We call it schizophrenia.

00:13:48.980 --> 00:13:50.670
JASON SILVA: Right.

00:13:50.670 --> 00:13:52.165
STEVEN KOTLER: So you don't
get to live in a permanent flow

00:13:52.165 --> 00:13:52.360
state.

00:13:52.360 --> 00:13:53.650
You can cycle through it.

00:13:53.650 --> 00:13:56.820
And you can shorten the
distance between cycles very,

00:13:56.820 --> 00:13:57.380
very quickly.

00:13:57.380 --> 00:13:58.520
So you can move through it.

00:13:58.520 --> 00:14:00.480
There's a lot ninjutsu to there.

00:14:00.480 --> 00:14:02.760
But I mean, what does
it mean for society

00:14:02.760 --> 00:14:05.897
if the 500% more productivity,
if you just-- I'm

00:14:05.897 --> 00:14:07.480
going to throw out
some other numbers.

00:14:07.480 --> 00:14:09.090
And they seem
really, really wonky.

00:14:09.090 --> 00:14:10.110
And we don't have
enough time to go

00:14:10.110 --> 00:14:11.430
into them because they're huge.

00:14:11.430 --> 00:14:15.370
Creativity in flow,
500% to 700% amplified.

00:14:15.370 --> 00:14:17.360
Motivation goes up
a similar level.

00:14:17.360 --> 00:14:19.180
Learning goes up
a similar level.

00:14:19.180 --> 00:14:21.530
So think about what this
means for education.

00:14:21.530 --> 00:14:24.170
There's studies done on college.

00:14:24.170 --> 00:14:27.070
If we can get kids through
college in three years,

00:14:27.070 --> 00:14:28.550
the savings and
the amount of money

00:14:28.550 --> 00:14:31.254
that comes into the
economy is significant.

00:14:31.254 --> 00:14:32.920
How do you accelerate
learning that way?

00:14:32.920 --> 00:14:33.470
We know how.

00:14:33.470 --> 00:14:35.430
Flow will already do it.

00:14:35.430 --> 00:14:38.000
We know that flow massively
increases the immune system.

00:14:38.000 --> 00:14:40.980
It boosts the immune system
and resets the nervous system.

00:14:40.980 --> 00:14:42.660
Herb Benson at
Harvard has said he

00:14:42.660 --> 00:14:44.740
thinks that flow is
responsible for most

00:14:44.740 --> 00:14:46.719
cases of so-called
spontaneous healing.

00:14:46.719 --> 00:14:49.010
He thinks it's actually the
neurobiology of flow that's

00:14:49.010 --> 00:14:49.702
underneath it.

00:14:49.702 --> 00:14:52.160
That may be overstepping the
case, as far as I'm concerned.

00:14:52.160 --> 00:14:54.350
But it's still intriguing
and worth pursuing.

00:14:54.350 --> 00:14:59.050
So health care, education,
technology, on, and on, and on.

00:14:59.050 --> 00:15:01.720
What it does is it puts
society into hyperdrive,

00:15:01.720 --> 00:15:03.479
or at least I think it does.

00:15:03.479 --> 00:15:04.520
JASON SILVA: I love this.

00:15:04.520 --> 00:15:07.182
So I want to connect this back
to the idea of technology,

00:15:07.182 --> 00:15:08.890
because you write a
lot about technology.

00:15:08.890 --> 00:15:11.900
And we've bonded around our
shared love of new construction

00:15:11.900 --> 00:15:12.910
kits for our reality.

00:15:12.910 --> 00:15:15.340
But OK, so we live
during disruptive times.

00:15:15.340 --> 00:15:17.650
We live during
exponential times.

00:15:17.650 --> 00:15:19.020
Everything is changing.

00:15:19.020 --> 00:15:20.810
Nobody really understands
why until they

00:15:20.810 --> 00:15:22.540
understand exponential change.

00:15:22.540 --> 00:15:26.310
Ray Kurzweil from Google
explains, we think linearly.

00:15:26.310 --> 00:15:28.620
Our brains evolved in a
linear and local world.

00:15:28.620 --> 00:15:31.250
But we live in a world
now that is exponential.

00:15:31.250 --> 00:15:34.130
And the best example is 30
linear steps gets you to 30;

00:15:34.130 --> 00:15:36.890
30 exponential steps
gets you to a billion.

00:15:36.890 --> 00:15:37.980
Now, what does this mean?

00:15:37.980 --> 00:15:40.250
It means that the smartphone
in your pocket today

00:15:40.250 --> 00:15:42.790
is a million times cheaper,
a million times smaller,

00:15:42.790 --> 00:15:44.750
a thousand times more
powerful than what

00:15:44.750 --> 00:15:47.410
used to be a $60 million
supercomputer that

00:15:47.410 --> 00:15:50.050
was half a building
in size 40 years ago.

00:15:50.050 --> 00:15:52.580
It means a young kid in
the savannas of Africa

00:15:52.580 --> 00:15:54.880
with a smartphone has
better communications

00:15:54.880 --> 00:15:57.740
technology than the US
president had 25 years ago.

00:15:57.740 --> 00:16:00.660
So new tools for new
realities, new possibilities.

00:16:00.660 --> 00:16:03.315
Now, you co-wrote
"Abundance," bestselling book

00:16:03.315 --> 00:16:04.190
with Peter Diamandis.

00:16:04.190 --> 00:16:05.830
You just released "Bold."

00:16:05.830 --> 00:16:08.610
And now you're releasing
"Tomorrowland," where science

00:16:08.610 --> 00:16:10.760
fiction becomes science fact.

00:16:10.760 --> 00:16:11.550
So talk to me.

00:16:11.550 --> 00:16:16.510
Muse with me a little bit about
this idea of these new brain

00:16:16.510 --> 00:16:18.272
scaffoldings that
we're creating and how

00:16:18.272 --> 00:16:19.730
they're ushering
in new possibility

00:16:19.730 --> 00:16:20.740
spaces for ourselves.

00:16:20.740 --> 00:16:22.281
And then tell me if
you think there's

00:16:22.281 --> 00:16:25.380
a connection between whether we
can leverage these flow states,

00:16:25.380 --> 00:16:28.170
if these new tools
require new minds in order

00:16:28.170 --> 00:16:31.932
to build the future
we want to build.

00:16:31.932 --> 00:16:33.265
STEVEN KOTLER: It's interesting.

00:16:33.265 --> 00:16:34.681
The thing that's
interesting to me

00:16:34.681 --> 00:16:36.930
about, and that I focus
on in "Tomorrowland,"

00:16:36.930 --> 00:16:38.140
is the next step out.

00:16:38.140 --> 00:16:39.920
Yes, we all know
that science fiction

00:16:39.920 --> 00:16:41.130
is becoming science fact.

00:16:41.130 --> 00:16:43.840
And that's everywhere.

00:16:43.840 --> 00:16:46.990
The random fact of the week--
50% of your body can now be

00:16:46.990 --> 00:16:47.895
replaced by bionics--

00:16:47.895 --> 00:16:48.770
JASON SILVA: Amazing.

00:16:48.770 --> 00:16:50.380
STEVEN KOTLER: which is insane.

00:16:50.380 --> 00:16:53.170
What's really interesting
to me about all this stuff

00:16:53.170 --> 00:16:56.590
is, for example, bionics.

00:16:56.590 --> 00:17:00.420
Not only do we have bionic
limbs for replacement parts

00:17:00.420 --> 00:17:02.850
and things like that for
paraplegics and quadriplegics.

00:17:02.850 --> 00:17:05.280
But we're starting to
get exoskeletons, so

00:17:05.280 --> 00:17:06.460
strap-on braces.

00:17:06.460 --> 00:17:09.319
There are now ankle braces
and knee braces, bionic ankle

00:17:09.319 --> 00:17:11.780
braces and knee braces
for the elderly.

00:17:11.780 --> 00:17:14.140
And they put energy
back into the system.

00:17:14.140 --> 00:17:17.329
Our brain evolved in such
a way that getting old

00:17:17.329 --> 00:17:19.050
was something that happened.

00:17:19.050 --> 00:17:20.760
There was nothing we
could do about it.

00:17:20.760 --> 00:17:23.089
And the number one
complaint about getting old

00:17:23.089 --> 00:17:24.619
is a loss of mobility.

00:17:24.619 --> 00:17:28.322
So we now have technology that
is taking that away here today.

00:17:28.322 --> 00:17:30.780
And it's only getting better,
because as Jason pointed out,

00:17:30.780 --> 00:17:32.750
these are all on
exponential growth curves.

00:17:32.750 --> 00:17:34.500
So what's interesting to
me about the transformation

00:17:34.500 --> 00:17:35.916
of science fiction
to science fact

00:17:35.916 --> 00:17:37.944
is less about the
whiz-bang technologies,

00:17:37.944 --> 00:17:39.360
and more about the
fact that we're

00:17:39.360 --> 00:17:43.530
starting to fuck with really
deep evolutionarily adaptive

00:17:43.530 --> 00:17:44.390
systems.

00:17:44.390 --> 00:17:46.760
We're starting to
really poke into what

00:17:46.760 --> 00:17:49.430
it means to be human at
a really, really, really

00:17:49.430 --> 00:17:50.087
deep level.

00:17:50.087 --> 00:17:51.920
And it's going to start
getting interesting.

00:17:51.920 --> 00:17:52.945
Because a lot of
the things-- it's

00:17:52.945 --> 00:17:54.111
not even our belief systems.

00:17:54.111 --> 00:17:56.480
It's the things that our
belief systems are built on.

00:17:56.480 --> 00:17:57.880
JASON SILVA: It's the substrate.

00:17:57.880 --> 00:17:58.440
STEVEN KOTLER: Exactly.

00:17:58.440 --> 00:17:59.050
That's exactly true.

00:17:59.050 --> 00:18:00.820
JASON SILVA: It's a great line
about Edward O. Wilson, where

00:18:00.820 --> 00:18:02.920
he says, we have decommissioned
natural selection.

00:18:02.920 --> 00:18:04.760
And now we must look
deep within ourselves

00:18:04.760 --> 00:18:06.800
to decide what we
wish to become.

00:18:06.800 --> 00:18:09.050
I mean, we've already
changed the physical,

00:18:09.050 --> 00:18:10.120
the external, world.

00:18:10.120 --> 00:18:11.320
If you look at a
city, what is that?

00:18:11.320 --> 00:18:12.990
Congealed intent, as
McKenna would say,

00:18:12.990 --> 00:18:14.650
congealed imagination.

00:18:14.650 --> 00:18:16.630
If you look at the
topography of Manhattan,

00:18:16.630 --> 00:18:19.490
that's shaped more by
mind, and agency, and will,

00:18:19.490 --> 00:18:22.230
and technology than
it is by geology.

00:18:22.230 --> 00:18:25.070
So the mind has already
trumped matter in so many ways.

00:18:25.070 --> 00:18:27.210
But it's like, now we're
experiencing a recursion,

00:18:27.210 --> 00:18:29.600
because now we're folding the
mind in on itself to start

00:18:29.600 --> 00:18:31.530
to play with biology itself.

00:18:31.530 --> 00:18:34.640
So biotechnology, mastering
the information processes

00:18:34.640 --> 00:18:37.520
of biology,
rewriting our genome.

00:18:37.520 --> 00:18:40.370
Having invented the gods,
we can turn into them.

00:18:40.370 --> 00:18:41.884
STEVEN KOTLER:
And the one-- I'll

00:18:41.884 --> 00:18:44.050
give you one example if we
want to talk about really

00:18:44.050 --> 00:18:46.970
crazy technology, mind
uploading, the idea that we

00:18:46.970 --> 00:18:49.310
can store ourselves
in silicon, upload

00:18:49.310 --> 00:18:50.640
our brains into computers.

00:18:50.640 --> 00:18:54.290
And it sounds absolutely crazy,
sounds like make-believe.

00:18:54.290 --> 00:18:55.627
People are working on it today.

00:18:55.627 --> 00:18:57.210
And it's actually a
multi-part system.

00:18:57.210 --> 00:18:59.620
And a couple of the parts,
like the playback mechanism,

00:18:59.620 --> 00:19:00.600
we have already.

00:19:00.600 --> 00:19:03.480
The VR devices that are at
Facebook, the next generation

00:19:03.480 --> 00:19:04.940
of Oculus can play it back.

00:19:04.940 --> 00:19:06.680
We've already got
things that we can

00:19:06.680 --> 00:19:09.140
plant in the brain that
can record basically all

00:19:09.140 --> 00:19:11.070
the inputs of all your senses.

00:19:11.070 --> 00:19:14.250
So nobody quite knows what
it is that constructs a life.

00:19:14.250 --> 00:19:17.730
But pretty soon, if we go
by Ray Kurzweil's numbers--

00:19:17.730 --> 00:19:20.380
and maybe you can, and maybe
you can't-- but his numbers,

00:19:20.380 --> 00:19:23.230
by 2045, we'll be able to
simulate a brain inside

00:19:23.230 --> 00:19:23.810
a computer.

00:19:23.810 --> 00:19:26.100
Which means we'll be able to
store ourselves in a computer.

00:19:26.100 --> 00:19:27.475
So the interesting
question to me

00:19:27.475 --> 00:19:31.030
is, think about
how much blood has

00:19:31.030 --> 00:19:33.780
been spilled in the past hundred
years in the name of religion.

00:19:33.780 --> 00:19:36.170
Think about how
much religion uses

00:19:36.170 --> 00:19:39.080
the threat of the hereafter
to steer morality and shape

00:19:39.080 --> 00:19:40.190
behavior.

00:19:40.190 --> 00:19:43.000
But what happens to
theological morality

00:19:43.000 --> 00:19:45.060
in the face of
technological immortality?

00:19:45.060 --> 00:19:46.890
And it sounds like
a crazy question,

00:19:46.890 --> 00:19:48.890
but it's a question we're
going to actually have

00:19:48.890 --> 00:19:50.044
to deal with this century.

00:19:50.044 --> 00:19:51.460
JASON SILVA: I
mean, it's no joke.

00:19:51.460 --> 00:19:53.060
I mean, Larry Page
from Google is

00:19:53.060 --> 00:19:56.200
funding Calico, the California
life extension company.

00:19:56.200 --> 00:19:58.410
Craig Venter created the
first artificial life form.

00:19:58.410 --> 00:20:00.076
And when they asked
him, are you worried

00:20:00.076 --> 00:20:02.400
about playing God, he
said, who's playing?

00:20:02.400 --> 00:20:05.020
I mean, there are
legitimately brilliant,

00:20:05.020 --> 00:20:08.140
smart, accomplished people
invested in this stuff.

00:20:08.140 --> 00:20:09.850
And the fact-- I
mean, what is it?

00:20:09.850 --> 00:20:13.600
It was Freeman Dyson that
says in the very near future,

00:20:13.600 --> 00:20:17.370
a new generation of artists will
write genomes with the fluency

00:20:17.370 --> 00:20:19.710
that Blake and
Byron wrote verses.

00:20:19.710 --> 00:20:23.190
So if you think of technology as
a conduit to new possibilities,

00:20:23.190 --> 00:20:26.100
new modes of human expression,
new modes of human agency-- so

00:20:26.100 --> 00:20:27.790
the technology of
the oil painting

00:20:27.790 --> 00:20:29.194
allowed van Gogh to emerge.

00:20:29.194 --> 00:20:30.860
The technology of the
musical instrument

00:20:30.860 --> 00:20:32.460
allowed Beethoven's genius.

00:20:32.460 --> 00:20:34.310
What are we going to
make with biology?

00:20:34.310 --> 00:20:37.750
What are our artists
going to "imagineer"

00:20:37.750 --> 00:20:39.492
with the canvas of life?

00:20:39.492 --> 00:20:41.450
STEVEN KOTLER: And it
sounds crazy, by the way.

00:20:41.450 --> 00:20:42.980
What he's saying sounds crazy.

00:20:42.980 --> 00:20:45.550
But synthetic biology--
which essentially

00:20:45.550 --> 00:20:47.850
treats genetic code
like computer code-- it

00:20:47.850 --> 00:20:49.940
allows us to write
life from scratch.

00:20:49.940 --> 00:20:52.359
Right now, it's new fuels,
new foods, new medicines.

00:20:52.359 --> 00:20:53.900
But a guy named
Andrew Hessel-- who's

00:20:53.900 --> 00:20:55.845
a friend of ours,
who's at Autodesk,

00:20:55.845 --> 00:20:57.720
he's a distinguished
researcher at Autodesk--

00:20:57.720 --> 00:21:00.070
is literally building
a DNA typewriter,

00:21:00.070 --> 00:21:02.640
meaning it's a
user-friendly interface

00:21:02.640 --> 00:21:04.390
for synthetic biology.

00:21:04.390 --> 00:21:06.600
So if you imagine what
happened to the web,

00:21:06.600 --> 00:21:08.890
the web had been
around for 20 years.

00:21:08.890 --> 00:21:10.950
Nobody but computer
scientists and the military

00:21:10.950 --> 00:21:12.750
are using it, because
there was no way to get on.

00:21:12.750 --> 00:21:14.166
You had to be a
computer scientist

00:21:14.166 --> 00:21:15.270
if you wanted to play.

00:21:15.270 --> 00:21:17.406
Marc Andreessen
comes along in 1993.

00:21:17.406 --> 00:21:20.230
He creates Mosaic,
which becomes Netscape.

00:21:20.230 --> 00:21:24.470
And we have 26 websites online
in 1993, 10,000 the next year,

00:21:24.470 --> 00:21:26.100
and a million the year after.

00:21:26.100 --> 00:21:28.080
Andrew's creating
a DNA typewriter,

00:21:28.080 --> 00:21:29.830
which is a
user-friendly interface

00:21:29.830 --> 00:21:30.850
for synthetic biology.

00:21:30.850 --> 00:21:34.050
So this idea that artists are
going to be programming life

00:21:34.050 --> 00:21:38.560
and creating in life is probably
five to 10 years away, longest.

00:21:38.560 --> 00:21:41.100
This is, it's here now.

00:21:41.100 --> 00:21:43.450
And I have no idea
what comes next.

00:21:43.450 --> 00:21:46.330
What I do think-- and
I've said this before.

00:21:46.330 --> 00:21:48.500
It's always been, especially
with these [? edge ?]

00:21:48.500 --> 00:21:49.735
technologies, there's
always subculture

00:21:49.735 --> 00:21:50.930
that drives it forward.

00:21:50.930 --> 00:21:53.650
And there's this-- I call
it the rebel instinct.

00:21:53.650 --> 00:21:56.740
Each generation seems to
outdo the next generation.

00:21:56.740 --> 00:21:58.030
So we did weird hair.

00:21:58.030 --> 00:21:59.530
And then we did weird clothes.

00:21:59.530 --> 00:22:02.745
And then we did body piercings
and some low-grade tattoos.

00:22:02.745 --> 00:22:04.620
And then we started
doing body modifications.

00:22:04.620 --> 00:22:06.890
And now we're doing
biohacking, the cutting edge.

00:22:06.890 --> 00:22:09.504
People are inserting
technology into their body.

00:22:09.504 --> 00:22:10.920
So I think what
we're going to see

00:22:10.920 --> 00:22:15.985
is the punk rockers of the
future with cat eyes, and cat

00:22:15.985 --> 00:22:18.110
tails, and angel--
there's already a guy.

00:22:18.110 --> 00:22:19.735
"Harper's" did that
story about the guy

00:22:19.735 --> 00:22:22.030
who's trying to build angel
wings that are surgically

00:22:22.030 --> 00:22:22.784
implanted.

00:22:22.784 --> 00:22:23.700
This is what's coming.

00:22:23.700 --> 00:22:26.060
So I do think it's
going to be a punk rock

00:22:26.060 --> 00:22:29.300
ethos that drives this forward.

00:22:29.300 --> 00:22:33.400
JASON SILVA: Now I want to ask
you about this idea of-- see,

00:22:33.400 --> 00:22:35.097
I think this stuff
is astonishing.

00:22:35.097 --> 00:22:37.430
I think if you pay attention
to what's happening-- well,

00:22:37.430 --> 00:22:40.125
if you pay attention to
anything-- as Darwin used

00:22:40.125 --> 00:22:41.850
to say, "Attention,
if sudden and close,

00:22:41.850 --> 00:22:44.540
graduates into surprise;
and this into astonishment;

00:22:44.540 --> 00:22:46.135
and this into
stupefied amazement."

00:22:46.135 --> 00:22:48.343
And yet most of us don't
pay attention to this stuff.

00:22:48.343 --> 00:22:52.100
Most of us go through our day,
kind of busy, kind of bored,

00:22:52.100 --> 00:22:54.740
kind of waiting for the next
hit of some kind of ecstasy.

00:22:54.740 --> 00:22:58.300
But I mean, we don't lose sleep
over these transformations.

00:22:58.300 --> 00:23:00.970
We are not in a permanent
state of astonishment.

00:23:00.970 --> 00:23:02.950
Can you tell me about
the brain chemistry

00:23:02.950 --> 00:23:06.210
of why we are walking around
half asleep most of the time,

00:23:06.210 --> 00:23:09.930
instead of marveling at
these new possibilities that

00:23:09.930 --> 00:23:11.805
are emerging, that are
going to fundamentally

00:23:11.805 --> 00:23:13.320
be changing humanity?

00:23:13.320 --> 00:23:15.749
Why isn't this on the front
page of everything, every day?

00:23:15.749 --> 00:23:17.790
I mean, I know you write
about this for "Forbes."

00:23:17.790 --> 00:23:19.498
I know you're seeing
more and more of it.

00:23:19.498 --> 00:23:21.740
But it's not everywhere
the way it should be.

00:23:21.740 --> 00:23:23.810
I mean, why isn't everybody
talking about this

00:23:23.810 --> 00:23:25.627
all the time?

00:23:25.627 --> 00:23:27.210
STEVEN KOTLER: That's
a real question?

00:23:27.210 --> 00:23:28.126
JASON SILVA: Honestly.

00:23:28.126 --> 00:23:30.330
Yes.

00:23:30.330 --> 00:23:32.335
STEVEN KOTLER: Well, I
don't know, actually.

00:23:32.335 --> 00:23:33.210
I wonder that myself.

00:23:33.210 --> 00:23:35.585
JASON SILVA: But don't you
think that there is an urgency

00:23:35.585 --> 00:23:38.620
here, the self determination
of the species being at stake.

00:23:38.620 --> 00:23:41.080
We should be setting
up playgrounds

00:23:41.080 --> 00:23:43.802
for new evolutionary paradigms
to be experimented with.

00:23:43.802 --> 00:23:45.760
STEVEN KOTLER: If you
want a biological answer,

00:23:45.760 --> 00:23:48.130
it's the amygdala, which
is the part of your brain

00:23:48.130 --> 00:23:49.120
that generates fear.

00:23:49.120 --> 00:23:54.540
And so consciousness
explained very, very simply,

00:23:54.540 --> 00:23:57.270
the brain takes in a
whole lot of information.

00:23:57.270 --> 00:23:59.070
And there's a bunch of filters.

00:23:59.070 --> 00:24:00.785
And the filters are
in front of what

00:24:00.785 --> 00:24:02.660
is pattern recognition
and future prediction.

00:24:02.660 --> 00:24:04.770
That's all that's going on
at a really deep level--

00:24:04.770 --> 00:24:06.144
information coming
in, grabbed by

00:24:06.144 --> 00:24:08.000
the senses, bunch of filters.

00:24:08.000 --> 00:24:09.540
And then we're
looking for patterns.

00:24:09.540 --> 00:24:10.500
And then we're
making predictions

00:24:10.500 --> 00:24:12.166
into the future based
on those patterns.

00:24:12.166 --> 00:24:14.770
That's essentially what your
brain is doing at all times.

00:24:14.770 --> 00:24:17.770
The first filter everything
hits is your amygdala.

00:24:17.770 --> 00:24:19.880
It's where all information goes.

00:24:19.880 --> 00:24:20.390
Why?

00:24:20.390 --> 00:24:22.970
Because the amygdala
governs fight or flight,

00:24:22.970 --> 00:24:24.900
safety and security.

00:24:24.900 --> 00:24:26.027
So fear--

00:24:26.027 --> 00:24:27.360
JASON SILVA: Gets our attention.

00:24:27.360 --> 00:24:29.443
STEVEN KOTLER: It gets--
but it's the first filter

00:24:29.443 --> 00:24:30.160
anybody puts up.

00:24:30.160 --> 00:24:32.470
It's the very first thing
anything that scares you,

00:24:32.470 --> 00:24:36.510
and all our cognitive biases
exist to narrow reality.

00:24:36.510 --> 00:24:38.940
If you look at what the
cognitive biases do,

00:24:38.940 --> 00:24:41.200
they're information
processing shortcuts.

00:24:41.200 --> 00:24:43.760
All biases are like processing
shortcuts gone wrong,

00:24:43.760 --> 00:24:45.760
because we take in
so much information.

00:24:45.760 --> 00:24:47.870
They've done
calculations, on average--

00:24:47.870 --> 00:24:49.880
and if you go by
the old numbers,

00:24:49.880 --> 00:24:53.000
it's 11 million bits of
information a second.

00:24:53.000 --> 00:24:54.500
If you go by the
new numbers, it's

00:24:54.500 --> 00:24:57.320
400 billion bits of
information a second.

00:24:57.320 --> 00:24:58.165
Whatever the case--

00:24:58.165 --> 00:24:58.420
JASON SILVA: It's
what's coming in.

00:24:58.420 --> 00:24:59.920
STEVEN KOTLER: --the
brain-- what's coming in.

00:24:59.920 --> 00:25:01.640
The brain is
massively overwhelmed.

00:25:01.640 --> 00:25:04.951
Your working memory can hold
about 40 bits of information

00:25:04.951 --> 00:25:05.450
at once.

00:25:05.450 --> 00:25:07.000
That's all you can
hold in your head,

00:25:07.000 --> 00:25:09.930
and you've got 400
billion bits coming in.

00:25:09.930 --> 00:25:13.640
So almost everything that
we think of as reality

00:25:13.640 --> 00:25:14.840
is not reality, obviously.

00:25:14.840 --> 00:25:16.340
It just gets thrown out.

00:25:16.340 --> 00:25:18.170
And the first thing
that's throwing it out

00:25:18.170 --> 00:25:19.530
is anything you're scared of.

00:25:19.530 --> 00:25:21.660
So why is this not
on the front page?

00:25:21.660 --> 00:25:23.709
Because all this stuff is scary.

00:25:23.709 --> 00:25:24.750
It can go horribly wrong.

00:25:24.750 --> 00:25:27.337
We were talking about what's
great with synthetic biology

00:25:27.337 --> 00:25:28.920
and what artists are
going to produce.

00:25:28.920 --> 00:25:30.490
I wrote an article
for "The Atlantic"

00:25:30.490 --> 00:25:34.120
not too long ago about
customizable bioweapons that

00:25:34.120 --> 00:25:37.230
can target individual people--
meaning I could now assassinate

00:25:37.230 --> 00:25:39.150
the president using
synthetic biology,

00:25:39.150 --> 00:25:40.790
and he's going to
think he got a cold.

00:25:40.790 --> 00:25:42.440
And it's only targeting
the president.

00:25:42.440 --> 00:25:44.600
And it's doable today.

00:25:44.600 --> 00:25:46.094
So this stuff gets scary fast.

00:25:46.094 --> 00:25:48.260
JASON SILVA: But see, that
does get very scary fast.

00:25:48.260 --> 00:25:50.950
But when the answer-- yes.

00:25:50.950 --> 00:25:52.954
But the answer that
I found Kurzweil

00:25:52.954 --> 00:25:54.620
has given, that I
found very compelling,

00:25:54.620 --> 00:25:55.850
is he said, well, that's
always been the case.

00:25:55.850 --> 00:25:58.000
Technology has always
been a double-edged sword.

00:25:58.000 --> 00:26:00.360
Fire can cook our foods
or burn our enemies.

00:26:00.360 --> 00:26:02.360
Perhaps the most powerful
information technology

00:26:02.360 --> 00:26:04.320
that's ever been
created is the alphabet.

00:26:04.320 --> 00:26:06.120
And the alphabet can
be used to compose

00:26:06.120 --> 00:26:10.240
beautiful Shakespearean sonnets
that expand our interior world.

00:26:10.240 --> 00:26:11.940
But the alphabet
can also be used

00:26:11.940 --> 00:26:14.972
to move people to kill each
other, and kill the other,

00:26:14.972 --> 00:26:15.930
and so on and so forth.

00:26:15.930 --> 00:26:18.870
So it's like, these
tools extend our will.

00:26:18.870 --> 00:26:22.810
But they can extend our
will in any direction.

00:26:22.810 --> 00:26:24.690
So yes, it's up to
us to make sure we

00:26:24.690 --> 00:26:25.850
use these things wisely.

00:26:25.850 --> 00:26:27.737
But that's always been the case.

00:26:27.737 --> 00:26:29.570
And we haven't destroyed
ourselves thus far.

00:26:29.570 --> 00:26:31.070
So I think we have a
pretty good track record.

00:26:31.070 --> 00:26:33.350
Also, if you look at the
work of Steven Pinker,

00:26:33.350 --> 00:26:34.320
he says the world
has been getting

00:26:34.320 --> 00:26:36.028
less violent for the
last couple decades.

00:26:36.028 --> 00:26:38.500
The world is less violent
now than it's ever been,

00:26:38.500 --> 00:26:41.060
contrary to the doom and gloom
things we see in the media.

00:26:41.060 --> 00:26:42.490
So do you think
that there's hope

00:26:42.490 --> 00:26:45.000
that, in spite of these new
tools being more dangerous,

00:26:45.000 --> 00:26:47.620
we somehow will
have the conscience

00:26:47.620 --> 00:26:48.674
to not destroy ourselves?

00:26:48.674 --> 00:26:50.340
STEVEN KOTLER: I don't
know if we're not

00:26:50.340 --> 00:26:51.160
going to destroy ourselves.

00:26:51.160 --> 00:26:53.576
I will-- to pull it back to
flow states, one of the things

00:26:53.576 --> 00:26:56.454
that we know about
flow-- and a lot of this

00:26:56.454 --> 00:26:57.995
has to do with all
the neurochemicals

00:26:57.995 --> 00:26:59.360
that show up in flow.

00:26:59.360 --> 00:27:01.090
Besides all the
performance enhancement

00:27:01.090 --> 00:27:02.690
and their addictive
nature, they're

00:27:02.690 --> 00:27:04.004
all social bonding chemicals.

00:27:04.004 --> 00:27:05.920
So if flow is one of
these technologies that's

00:27:05.920 --> 00:27:08.000
going to drive us
into the future--

00:27:08.000 --> 00:27:10.370
all of the social
bonding chemicals, all

00:27:10.370 --> 00:27:13.240
the norepinephrine and
dopamine which show up in flow,

00:27:13.240 --> 00:27:15.260
that's romantic love.

00:27:15.260 --> 00:27:17.430
Endorphins, that's
maternal love.

00:27:17.430 --> 00:27:20.070
Anandamide is that same kind
of psychoactive chemical

00:27:20.070 --> 00:27:23.014
that's in marijuana, makes
you open to new ideas,

00:27:23.014 --> 00:27:23.930
and love your friends.

00:27:23.930 --> 00:27:25.230
JASON SILVA: We love that.

00:27:25.230 --> 00:27:27.600
STEVEN KOTLER: So these are
really potent social bonding

00:27:27.600 --> 00:27:28.100
chemicals.

00:27:28.100 --> 00:27:30.330
The point is that
flow expands empathy.

00:27:30.330 --> 00:27:31.880
And a lot of these
new technologies

00:27:31.880 --> 00:27:33.804
seem to be able play with that.

00:27:33.804 --> 00:27:34.720
We can expand empathy.

00:27:34.720 --> 00:27:36.261
You were talking
about the difference

00:27:36.261 --> 00:27:37.541
between states and stages.

00:27:37.541 --> 00:27:38.540
JASON SILVA: Absolutely.

00:27:38.540 --> 00:27:40.414
I mean, when you start
talking about empathy,

00:27:40.414 --> 00:27:43.530
I get excited, because there's
a great line from "Interstellar"

00:27:43.530 --> 00:27:45.580
that talked about how
empathy rarely extends

00:27:45.580 --> 00:27:46.710
beyond our line of sight.

00:27:46.710 --> 00:27:48.824
And one of the things that
our new technologies do

00:27:48.824 --> 00:27:49.990
is extend our line of sight.

00:27:49.990 --> 00:27:51.540
I mean, if you think
virtual reality,

00:27:51.540 --> 00:27:53.310
that potentially is
an engine of empathy.

00:27:53.310 --> 00:27:55.101
You put somebody inside
of a virtual space,

00:27:55.101 --> 00:27:58.200
place them in a Syrian refugee
camp, you extend their empathy.

00:27:58.200 --> 00:28:00.024
A lot more difficult to ignore.

00:28:00.024 --> 00:28:02.440
So you think the combination
of these external technology,

00:28:02.440 --> 00:28:03.600
and potentially
these flow states

00:28:03.600 --> 00:28:05.280
and this internal
technologies could

00:28:05.280 --> 00:28:07.196
allow us to create a
more empathetic species--

00:28:07.196 --> 00:28:09.730
could actually create
a shift that scales?

00:28:09.730 --> 00:28:11.934
STEVEN KOTLER: Look at
the-- you've got to--

00:28:11.934 --> 00:28:13.600
I disagree with the
"Interstellar" line,

00:28:13.600 --> 00:28:14.180
for example.

00:28:14.180 --> 00:28:17.230
Because what religion
is, basically,

00:28:17.230 --> 00:28:20.880
is a way to extend empathy
beyond clan and kin.

00:28:20.880 --> 00:28:23.060
That's what it was.

00:28:23.060 --> 00:28:24.399
You go back 500 years.

00:28:24.399 --> 00:28:26.940
If I wasn't related to you, if
you didn't live in my village,

00:28:26.940 --> 00:28:27.565
you were other.

00:28:27.565 --> 00:28:29.450
And I wanted to fight
you and kill you.

00:28:29.450 --> 00:28:31.770
Religion allowed
us to extend that.

00:28:31.770 --> 00:28:32.830
Suddenly, oh, wow.

00:28:32.830 --> 00:28:33.560
He's a Christian?

00:28:33.560 --> 00:28:34.390
I'm a Christian.

00:28:34.390 --> 00:28:36.190
OK, we don't have
to kill each other.

00:28:36.190 --> 00:28:38.410
So we've seen what
these-- we've also

00:28:38.410 --> 00:28:40.170
seen them backfire, of course.

00:28:40.170 --> 00:28:43.400
But we've seen technology,
language, massively

00:28:43.400 --> 00:28:44.980
extend empathy before.

00:28:44.980 --> 00:28:49.570
This is a much more
visceral version of it.

00:28:49.570 --> 00:28:51.570
I mean, I don't think
it's everybody on ecstasy.

00:28:51.570 --> 00:28:54.270
But it definitely opens you up.

00:28:54.270 --> 00:28:55.910
And you're closer to it.

00:28:55.910 --> 00:28:58.610
So I think there's
a lot of hope.

00:28:58.610 --> 00:29:02.070
But I also think the thing
about exponential technology

00:29:02.070 --> 00:29:04.920
at this point is it does
put the power of God

00:29:04.920 --> 00:29:06.314
into the hands of individuals.

00:29:06.314 --> 00:29:07.730
And that's what's
different today.

00:29:07.730 --> 00:29:10.240
JASON SILVA: Promethean--
stealing fire from the gods.

00:29:10.240 --> 00:29:13.319
Well, tease the name
of your next book.

00:29:13.319 --> 00:29:14.610
STEVEN KOTLER: "Stealing Fire."

00:29:14.610 --> 00:29:15.276
JASON SILVA: OK.

00:29:15.276 --> 00:29:18.850
So it was originally-- we
had a whole conversation

00:29:18.850 --> 00:29:21.750
about this idea of
mapping the highest

00:29:21.750 --> 00:29:23.880
possible states of
human consciousness,

00:29:23.880 --> 00:29:26.830
mapping our ecstasies,
creating a kind of cartography

00:29:26.830 --> 00:29:29.130
of ecstatic states.

00:29:29.130 --> 00:29:32.060
And so can you talk a little
bit about "Stealing Fire,"

00:29:32.060 --> 00:29:34.550
flow states, and how these
emerging technologies are

00:29:34.550 --> 00:29:38.680
allowing us to basically get
higher than we've ever gotten;

00:29:38.680 --> 00:29:41.610
to explore new
spaces of ecstatic

00:29:41.610 --> 00:29:44.430
rapture; the neurobiology
of mystical experience;

00:29:44.430 --> 00:29:45.530
and so on and so forth.

00:29:45.530 --> 00:29:46.850
Hacking nirvana.

00:29:46.850 --> 00:29:47.950
Beyond flow.

00:29:47.950 --> 00:29:48.830
Hacking nirvana.

00:29:48.830 --> 00:29:51.042
STEVEN KOTLER: Well, so
the idea that-- Jason's

00:29:51.042 --> 00:29:52.750
talking about a book
that I'm writing now

00:29:52.750 --> 00:29:55.010
with my partner on the Flow
Genome Project, Jamie Wheal.

00:29:55.010 --> 00:29:56.343
And it's called "Stealing Fire."

00:29:56.343 --> 00:29:59.250
And the core idea is
there's a whole swatch

00:29:59.250 --> 00:30:03.230
of experiences-- psychedelic
experiences, drug experiences,

00:30:03.230 --> 00:30:05.766
flow states, so-called mystical
experiences, et cetera, et

00:30:05.766 --> 00:30:06.266
cetera.

00:30:06.266 --> 00:30:08.910
And when you start adding them
together and looking at them,

00:30:08.910 --> 00:30:10.368
first of all what
you find is, from

00:30:10.368 --> 00:30:14.000
a neurobiological perspective,
very, very, very similar.

00:30:14.000 --> 00:30:17.130
For example, meditative
states and flow.

00:30:17.130 --> 00:30:20.936
In flow, the dorsal lateral
prefrontal cortex goes off.

00:30:20.936 --> 00:30:21.810
We talked about that.

00:30:21.810 --> 00:30:23.393
But another portion
your brain, called

00:30:23.393 --> 00:30:25.420
the medial orbital
prefrontal cortex--

00:30:25.420 --> 00:30:28.260
which is creative
self-expression-- goes crazy,

00:30:28.260 --> 00:30:29.630
becomes really hyperactive.

00:30:29.630 --> 00:30:31.987
Because flow, creativity,
goes through the roof,

00:30:31.987 --> 00:30:34.070
this portion of the brain
gets really hyperactive.

00:30:34.070 --> 00:30:35.640
In meditative
states, because you

00:30:35.640 --> 00:30:37.540
don't need creative
decision making,

00:30:37.540 --> 00:30:40.010
that portion of the
brain shuts off.

00:30:40.010 --> 00:30:40.920
Other things turn up.

00:30:40.920 --> 00:30:42.700
When you look at
it, it's basically

00:30:42.700 --> 00:30:44.324
a set of knobs and levers.

00:30:44.324 --> 00:30:45.740
We're turning down
certain things.

00:30:45.740 --> 00:30:46.820
We're turning up certain things.

00:30:46.820 --> 00:30:48.695
We're turning on certain
things, turning off.

00:30:48.695 --> 00:30:50.700
But it's a set category.

00:30:50.700 --> 00:30:54.350
And what we're discovering,
really in the past 100 years,

00:30:54.350 --> 00:30:56.170
and much more in
the past 25 years,

00:30:56.170 --> 00:30:58.810
is there's-- I call it an upper
possibility space of human

00:30:58.810 --> 00:31:02.290
experience that has almost
been completely off the map.

00:31:02.290 --> 00:31:04.804
And by upper, I mean
north of happiness.

00:31:04.804 --> 00:31:06.720
Things start at happiness,
and they get weird.

00:31:06.720 --> 00:31:07.511
JASON SILVA: Right.

00:31:07.511 --> 00:31:10.160
STEVEN KOTLER: But there's
a whole huge space up there

00:31:10.160 --> 00:31:11.360
that we haven't inhabited.

00:31:11.360 --> 00:31:14.010
And when people tripped into
it, we thought they were crazy.

00:31:14.010 --> 00:31:16.620
We burned them at
stakes for a long time,

00:31:16.620 --> 00:31:18.150
or we called them drug addicts.

00:31:18.150 --> 00:31:20.490
And we wrote them off and
banished them, whatever.

00:31:20.490 --> 00:31:22.250
All this stuff is
being opened up.

00:31:22.250 --> 00:31:24.072
And more interestingly,
it's being

00:31:24.072 --> 00:31:25.155
opened up technologically.

00:31:25.155 --> 00:31:28.610
And it seems like when things
get opened up technologically,

00:31:28.610 --> 00:31:30.170
we're less afraid of them.

00:31:30.170 --> 00:31:32.620
Michael Persinger
creates the God Helmet.

00:31:32.620 --> 00:31:36.940
He basically puts in on, it
shoots electromagnetic fields

00:31:36.940 --> 00:31:38.220
into your right temporal lobe.

00:31:38.220 --> 00:31:39.910
We know right temporal
lobe epilepsy,

00:31:39.910 --> 00:31:41.787
when this part of the
brain gets excited,

00:31:41.787 --> 00:31:43.120
we have out-of-body experiences.

00:31:43.120 --> 00:31:45.226
We have near-death experiences.

00:31:45.226 --> 00:31:46.850
By the way, the same
part of your brain

00:31:46.850 --> 00:31:48.160
gets very excited in dreaming.

00:31:48.160 --> 00:31:50.190
So we have this
experience every night.

00:31:50.190 --> 00:31:53.287
But we can now stimulate
this with technology.

00:31:53.287 --> 00:31:54.370
Doesn't work all the time.

00:31:54.370 --> 00:31:55.330
Doesn't work for everybody.

00:31:55.330 --> 00:31:57.079
But we're getting
better and better at it.

00:31:57.079 --> 00:31:59.900
And people are-- we might be
hesitant about taking a drug,

00:31:59.900 --> 00:32:00.770
or we write it off.

00:32:00.770 --> 00:32:02.389
But if it's
technologically mediated,

00:32:02.389 --> 00:32:03.930
we're a lot more
comfortable with it.

00:32:03.930 --> 00:32:04.635
JASON SILVA: A lot
more open to it.

00:32:04.635 --> 00:32:06.990
STEVEN KOTLER: It's
allowing us to open up

00:32:06.990 --> 00:32:09.360
this really crazy space that
we don't really understand.

00:32:09.360 --> 00:32:10.110
JASON SILVA: Yeah.

00:32:10.110 --> 00:32:12.500
Well, I mean, it
captures my imagination,

00:32:12.500 --> 00:32:15.170
especially when you
say north of happiness.

00:32:15.170 --> 00:32:17.170
Because I mean, what is
the self-help movement,

00:32:17.170 --> 00:32:19.330
the happiness movement,
billion-dollar industries.

00:32:19.330 --> 00:32:21.180
People trying to figure out
new metrics for happiness

00:32:21.180 --> 00:32:23.388
because it turns out that
getting everything you want

00:32:23.388 --> 00:32:25.240
is not going to make you happy.

00:32:25.240 --> 00:32:26.944
And that experiences,
for example,

00:32:26.944 --> 00:32:28.360
are more valuable
than things when

00:32:28.360 --> 00:32:30.780
it comes to longer-form
satisfaction and satiation.

00:32:30.780 --> 00:32:33.630
But we are an
existential species.

00:32:33.630 --> 00:32:36.640
We are an agitated species.

00:32:36.640 --> 00:32:38.536
With our minds, we can
ponder the infinite.

00:32:38.536 --> 00:32:39.910
Now I'm channeling
Ernest Becker.

00:32:39.910 --> 00:32:41.472
We can ponder the
infinite, yet we're

00:32:41.472 --> 00:32:44.130
housed in heart pumping, breath
gasping, decaying bodies.

00:32:44.130 --> 00:32:47.710
So our greatest
ecstasies are haunted,

00:32:47.710 --> 00:32:50.900
are shadowed by the fact
that they are temporary,

00:32:50.900 --> 00:32:53.269
that we are finite-- no
matter how many times we get

00:32:53.269 --> 00:32:54.810
the goosebumps and
are moved to tears

00:32:54.810 --> 00:32:57.810
by beautiful art, or beautiful
ecstasy, or beautiful rhapsody.

00:32:57.810 --> 00:32:59.310
So my question for
you-- when you're

00:32:59.310 --> 00:33:01.140
talking about
north of happiness,

00:33:01.140 --> 00:33:03.760
technological
mediation, I'm reminded

00:33:03.760 --> 00:33:06.330
of David Pearce's work,
"The Hedonistic Imperative."

00:33:06.330 --> 00:33:08.140
Are you familiar
with David Pearce?

00:33:08.140 --> 00:33:10.070
He's a transhumanist
philosopher that

00:33:10.070 --> 00:33:12.620
believes that we are going
to institute a paradise

00:33:12.620 --> 00:33:14.350
engineering, as
he calls it, where

00:33:14.350 --> 00:33:16.320
we're going to be using
new biotechnologies

00:33:16.320 --> 00:33:19.120
and nanotechnologies to
shift our hedonic treadmill

00:33:19.120 --> 00:33:21.680
and to literally
neuroengineer gradients

00:33:21.680 --> 00:33:25.550
of bliss that will make even our
greatest ecstasies today pale.

00:33:25.550 --> 00:33:29.415
He calls them our Darwinian,
old-school ecstasies

00:33:29.415 --> 00:33:31.040
compared to what
we're going to create.

00:33:31.040 --> 00:33:32.930
Where do you stand on
that idea, not just

00:33:32.930 --> 00:33:35.820
in terms of the science, but
in terms of the poet in you?

00:33:35.820 --> 00:33:39.730
Does this excite you, this
idea of creating spaces

00:33:39.730 --> 00:33:45.065
so much more north of happy, and
what that's going to be like?

00:33:45.065 --> 00:33:47.440
STEVEN KOTLER: So we have
something called an hedonic set

00:33:47.440 --> 00:33:47.940
point.

00:33:47.940 --> 00:33:49.780
An hedonic set point
basically means

00:33:49.780 --> 00:33:54.600
that somewhere between ages six
and 12, the amount of happiness

00:33:54.600 --> 00:33:57.210
and sadness you're going to
feel in life is pretty much set.

00:33:57.210 --> 00:34:01.164
It's why you feel the same
emotionally at 10, at 20,

00:34:01.164 --> 00:34:02.510
at 30, at 40.

00:34:02.510 --> 00:34:04.661
It's roughly the same
bandwidth of emotion.

00:34:04.661 --> 00:34:06.910
It's because we have these
things called emotional set

00:34:06.910 --> 00:34:07.090
points.

00:34:07.090 --> 00:34:08.250
And they get locked down.

00:34:10.870 --> 00:34:13.530
I'm less interested
in the super-ecstatic.

00:34:13.530 --> 00:34:15.949
I just think it's interesting.

00:34:15.949 --> 00:34:17.334
But it's very bizarre.

00:34:17.334 --> 00:34:19.000
And I have no idea
what comes from that.

00:34:19.000 --> 00:34:21.300
But what happens if we
can just shift everybody

00:34:21.300 --> 00:34:24.770
and we're 3% happier?

00:34:24.770 --> 00:34:26.550
And that's really,
really possible.

00:34:26.550 --> 00:34:29.228
For example, we know--
mass amounts of research

00:34:29.228 --> 00:34:30.644
back this up--
that the people who

00:34:30.644 --> 00:34:33.080
have the most flow in
their lives, it's often

00:34:33.080 --> 00:34:34.469
said that people with the
most flow in their lives

00:34:34.469 --> 00:34:35.540
are the happiest
people on Earth.

00:34:35.540 --> 00:34:36.870
And it's actually a misnomer.

00:34:36.870 --> 00:34:38.664
Happiness is a
temporary condition.

00:34:38.664 --> 00:34:40.330
People with the most
flow in their lives

00:34:40.330 --> 00:34:42.690
score off the charts
on life satisfaction

00:34:42.690 --> 00:34:43.650
and well being tests.

00:34:43.650 --> 00:34:45.950
So it's meaning and it's
overall possibility.

00:34:45.950 --> 00:34:47.199
JASON SILVA: Beyond happiness.

00:34:47.199 --> 00:34:49.150
STEVEN KOTLER: Right,
it's beyond happiness.

00:34:49.150 --> 00:34:51.770
So we know flow, repeated
exposure to flow,

00:34:51.770 --> 00:34:53.840
can shift your
emotional set point.

00:34:53.840 --> 00:34:57.310
It's one of the only things
that can actually shift this.

00:34:57.310 --> 00:34:59.360
So that's where it starts
to get interesting.

00:34:59.360 --> 00:35:00.750
Because we know
this is possible.

00:35:00.750 --> 00:35:01.880
We know this is doable.

00:35:01.880 --> 00:35:05.200
So what happens if we move an
entire society a couple degrees

00:35:05.200 --> 00:35:06.140
up that ladder?

00:35:06.140 --> 00:35:07.314
That's interesting to me.

00:35:07.314 --> 00:35:08.980
JASON SILVA: That's
a happy place to be.

00:35:08.980 --> 00:35:11.146
STEVEN KOTLER: Well, it
means a whole lot less fear.

00:35:11.146 --> 00:35:14.000
So that first filter we were
talking about gets damped down.

00:35:14.000 --> 00:35:16.466
And then the possibility
space gets really interesting.

00:35:16.466 --> 00:35:17.174
JASON SILVA: Wow.

00:35:17.174 --> 00:35:18.890
That gets me very happy, bro.

00:35:18.890 --> 00:35:21.830
STEVEN KOTLER: I'm so glad.

00:35:21.830 --> 00:35:27.845
JASON SILVA: So can we talk
a little bit about your work?

00:35:27.845 --> 00:35:29.970
People say that people who
live in their flow state

00:35:29.970 --> 00:35:32.930
kind of build their
whole lives around it.

00:35:32.930 --> 00:35:35.190
You live in a dog
sanctuary that you

00:35:35.190 --> 00:35:37.934
created, which I think is one
of the most amazing things ever.

00:35:37.934 --> 00:35:40.100
Because you're this amazingly
gifted writer, writing

00:35:40.100 --> 00:35:41.350
all these New York
bestsellers, but you

00:35:41.350 --> 00:35:42.450
live with all these dogs.

00:35:42.450 --> 00:35:44.700
Can you tell me a little bit
about what you discovered

00:35:44.700 --> 00:35:47.519
about animals, and how that
gets you into your flow state,

00:35:47.519 --> 00:35:48.060
a little bit?

00:35:48.060 --> 00:35:49.190
STEVEN KOTLER: Well,
a couple of things.

00:35:49.190 --> 00:35:51.460
JASON SILVA: I'm in awe of
that aspect of your life.

00:35:51.460 --> 00:35:53.460
STEVEN KOTLER: I run a animal
sanctuary called Rancho de

00:35:53.460 --> 00:35:53.960
Chihuahua.

00:35:53.960 --> 00:35:56.330
And we deal with hospice
care and special needs care

00:35:56.330 --> 00:35:58.490
for really sick small dogs.

00:35:58.490 --> 00:36:00.374
And really, really sick.

00:36:00.374 --> 00:36:01.790
Most of our animals
show up to us,

00:36:01.790 --> 00:36:03.340
they come directly
from vets often,

00:36:03.340 --> 00:36:06.680
with a month to live, two months
to live, that kind of thing.

00:36:06.680 --> 00:36:08.740
Flow is at the heart of
