00:36:08.740 --> 00:36:11.025
And as I said earlier, it
boosts the immune system.

00:36:11.025 --> 00:36:12.400
It resets the
[INAUDIBLE] system.

00:36:12.400 --> 00:36:15.540
Our animals live for
a really long time.

00:36:15.540 --> 00:36:18.660
So we actually do put these--
we were talking about,

00:36:18.660 --> 00:36:20.430
is flow trainable?

00:36:20.430 --> 00:36:22.330
We put our dogs in
the flow all the time.

00:36:22.330 --> 00:36:26.097
It's actually not hard.

00:36:26.097 --> 00:36:28.180
By the way, we don't know
if it's all animals that

00:36:28.180 --> 00:36:29.180
are hard-wired for flow.

00:36:29.180 --> 00:36:30.320
We know it's dogs.

00:36:30.320 --> 00:36:33.470
And we know at some point
down the mammalian chain,

00:36:33.470 --> 00:36:34.740
it probably cuts off.

00:36:34.740 --> 00:36:36.280
And we don't know where.

00:36:36.280 --> 00:36:38.806
But we absolutely know
dogs can get into flow.

00:36:38.806 --> 00:36:40.430
What else do you want
me to talk about?

00:36:40.430 --> 00:36:40.780
JASON SILVA: No, no.

00:36:40.780 --> 00:36:41.980
I just wanted you
to talk about that.

00:36:41.980 --> 00:36:44.040
But I also want to bring
up the subject, just

00:36:44.040 --> 00:36:45.870
because usually when
I'm in a flow state,

00:36:45.870 --> 00:36:48.200
I'm usually very quickly
marveling at something,

00:36:48.200 --> 00:36:49.270
because I'm a very
curious person.

00:36:49.270 --> 00:36:50.820
So I'm always like, I want
to get into a flow state

00:36:50.820 --> 00:36:51.687
and see a movie.

00:36:51.687 --> 00:36:53.270
I want to get into
a flow state and go

00:36:53.270 --> 00:36:55.310
for a walk in some
beautiful spot,

00:36:55.310 --> 00:36:56.870
maybe like Big Sur or whatever.

00:36:56.870 --> 00:36:59.550
And there was this great book
by Allison Griffiths called

00:36:59.550 --> 00:37:00.810
"Shivers Down Your Spine."

00:37:00.810 --> 00:37:02.690
It talked about cinema,
Gothic cathedrals,

00:37:02.690 --> 00:37:03.847
and the immersive view.

00:37:03.847 --> 00:37:05.930
And so she was talking
about external technologies

00:37:05.930 --> 00:37:08.800
that we use to trigger
these states of rapture,

00:37:08.800 --> 00:37:09.690
states of awe.

00:37:09.690 --> 00:37:12.210
And she said Gothic cathedrals
are designed in a certain way

00:37:12.210 --> 00:37:14.770
to put you in touch with the
sublime, to hack your brain,

00:37:14.770 --> 00:37:16.520
and put you in awe right away.

00:37:16.520 --> 00:37:18.680
The modern incarnation of
that, the IMAX Theater.

00:37:18.680 --> 00:37:21.180
She says you go into an IMAX
Theater, and right off the bat,

00:37:21.180 --> 00:37:24.380
the space is already doing
something to your perception.

00:37:24.380 --> 00:37:26.730
It's already doing
something to your mood.

00:37:26.730 --> 00:37:28.630
And there's been a
lot of recent science

00:37:28.630 --> 00:37:30.402
about this emotion of awe.

00:37:30.402 --> 00:37:32.360
That it turns out that
experiences that stretch

00:37:32.360 --> 00:37:34.980
your perceptual boundaries
force you to create

00:37:34.980 --> 00:37:36.500
new maps of the world.

00:37:36.500 --> 00:37:38.800
And in assimilating
these new experiences,

00:37:38.800 --> 00:37:41.610
you experience this
cognitive ecstasy, this awe.

00:37:41.610 --> 00:37:43.610
And after the moment
passes, you're

00:37:43.610 --> 00:37:46.361
left with increased
feelings, residual feelings,

00:37:46.361 --> 00:37:48.360
of heightened creativity,
heightened well being,

00:37:48.360 --> 00:37:50.880
heightened satisfaction--
which is already wonderful.

00:37:50.880 --> 00:37:53.135
And additionally, these
experiences of awe

00:37:53.135 --> 00:37:54.480
are anti-inflammatory.

00:37:54.480 --> 00:37:56.060
So they're also good for you.

00:37:56.060 --> 00:37:59.609
So what is your take on
this side emotion of awe

00:37:59.609 --> 00:38:00.900
and where it fits in with flow?

00:38:00.900 --> 00:38:01.180
STEVEN KOTLER: Yeah.

00:38:01.180 --> 00:38:02.790
What we know about
awe, actually,

00:38:02.790 --> 00:38:06.720
is-- so one of the triggers
for flow, one of the things

00:38:06.720 --> 00:38:09.490
that will drive us into
flow is what's technically

00:38:09.490 --> 00:38:10.780
called a rich environment.

00:38:10.780 --> 00:38:13.070
Which is a fancy way of
saying lots of novelty,

00:38:13.070 --> 00:38:15.570
lots of complexity, lots
of unpredictability.

00:38:15.570 --> 00:38:17.920
Complexity is what triggers awe.

00:38:17.920 --> 00:38:20.320
So when you stare
up at the night sky,

00:38:20.320 --> 00:38:24.750
and you see a billion galaxies,
and you cannot process it,

00:38:24.750 --> 00:38:27.220
your conscious mind
literally cannot process it.

00:38:27.220 --> 00:38:29.960
So what happens in flow is
we trade conscious processing

00:38:29.960 --> 00:38:31.160
for subconscious processing.

00:38:31.160 --> 00:38:33.260
Flow is the only
time we actually

00:38:33.260 --> 00:38:35.540
get to watch the
subconscious mind work.

00:38:35.540 --> 00:38:37.760
And the reason it's
such a weird state,

00:38:37.760 --> 00:38:40.510
conscious thought travels
about 150 miles an hour.

00:38:40.510 --> 00:38:43.870
Subconscious thought, 2,000
to 5,000 miles an hour.

00:38:43.870 --> 00:38:46.970
So it's hyperspeed
decision making.

00:38:46.970 --> 00:38:48.759
Awe is the front
edge of a flow state.

00:38:48.759 --> 00:38:50.300
So when you look up
at the night sky,

00:38:50.300 --> 00:38:52.170
and you get sucked
in, and time dilation,

00:38:52.170 --> 00:38:53.700
everything freezes for a minute.

00:38:53.700 --> 00:38:56.120
That's actually the front
end of the flow state.

00:38:56.120 --> 00:38:59.320
And so we know from-- this
is Teresa Amabile's work

00:38:59.320 --> 00:39:00.350
at Harvard.

00:39:00.350 --> 00:39:02.908
She figured out that the height
in creativity that shows up

00:39:02.908 --> 00:39:05.730
in flow actually outlasts
