I had to be really--

00:50:53.110 --> 00:50:54.260
the trip had to scare me.

00:50:54.260 --> 00:50:55.130
The journey had to scare me.

00:50:55.130 --> 00:50:56.610
That night before,
I wasn't sleeping

00:50:56.610 --> 00:50:58.735
for weeks, because I was
going off to the Himalayas

00:50:58.735 --> 00:51:00.080
to go chase whatever.

00:51:00.080 --> 00:51:03.630
I would really work myself
into a state, a really negative

00:51:03.630 --> 00:51:06.180
state, so that even a little
bit of a positive experience

00:51:06.180 --> 00:51:07.180
could kick me into flow.

00:51:07.180 --> 00:51:08.740
It didn't take
much at that point,

00:51:08.740 --> 00:51:11.960
because I had freaked myself
out so much ahead of time.

00:51:11.960 --> 00:51:14.810
So yeah.

00:51:14.810 --> 00:51:17.860
Both Jason and myself will tell
you we're both flow junkies.

00:51:17.860 --> 00:51:20.280
And we're both totally neurotic.

00:51:20.280 --> 00:51:23.200
And a lot of the reason
I think I got into this

00:51:23.200 --> 00:51:26.090
is because it's bad up here.

00:51:26.090 --> 00:51:29.040
I've got to do a lot
to get out of here

00:51:29.040 --> 00:51:31.650
under normal conditions.

00:51:31.650 --> 00:51:32.590
JASON SILVA: I agree.

00:51:32.590 --> 00:51:34.090
Very neurotic.

00:51:34.090 --> 00:51:35.559
And not only that,
but I'm obsessed

00:51:35.559 --> 00:51:38.100
with Ernest Becker, who wrote
the book "The Denial of Death,"

00:51:38.100 --> 00:51:41.410
because I'm extremely haunted
by the idea of transience

00:51:41.410 --> 00:51:42.520
and mortality.

00:51:42.520 --> 00:51:45.210
And I can vouch for the fact
that when I'm in a flow state,

00:51:45.210 --> 00:51:47.652
it's the only time
when bliss rules.

00:51:47.652 --> 00:51:49.110
There's no thoughts
about, oh, this

00:51:49.110 --> 00:51:50.276
is all going to end one day.

00:51:50.276 --> 00:51:53.180
So why even be excited, because
it's all temporary, anyway.

00:51:53.180 --> 00:51:54.960
And everything
dissolves into nothing.

00:51:54.960 --> 00:51:56.650
But when I'm in a
flow state, and I'm

00:51:56.650 --> 00:51:58.570
watching an amazing movie or I'm
listening to beautiful music,

00:51:58.570 --> 00:52:00.105
or I'm being blown
away by the ideas

00:52:00.105 --> 00:52:01.780
that somebody's
sharing-- holy shit.

00:52:01.780 --> 00:52:02.970
I'm in the eternal now.

00:52:02.970 --> 00:52:06.400
And death doesn't exist.

00:52:06.400 --> 00:52:08.180
MAN 1: Yeah.

00:52:08.180 --> 00:52:09.530
I'm curious.

00:52:09.530 --> 00:52:12.555
How are these flow states--
you talk about extreme sports.

00:52:12.555 --> 00:52:14.480
I've been a surfer for 30 years.

00:52:14.480 --> 00:52:17.560
In the last 10 years, the
shit that's been happening,

00:52:17.560 --> 00:52:18.940
you can't even believe it.

00:52:18.940 --> 00:52:21.920
And is it epigenetics
through YouTube?

00:52:21.920 --> 00:52:24.180
Or is it-- people are getting
into these flow states.

00:52:24.180 --> 00:52:25.596
And you see somebody
do something.

00:52:25.596 --> 00:52:27.690
It's like that
Laird Hamilton photo

00:52:27.690 --> 00:52:30.070
that came on "Surfer" magazine.

00:52:30.070 --> 00:52:32.785
I mean, literally, just
everyone was, what the hell?

00:52:32.785 --> 00:52:35.336
And five years later,
everybody's doing it.

00:52:35.336 --> 00:52:36.710
And I see it over
and over again.

00:52:36.710 --> 00:52:37.430
And it just fascinates me.

00:52:37.430 --> 00:52:39.721
STEVEN KOTLER: That was one
of the-- one of the reasons

00:52:39.721 --> 00:52:41.760
that I got interested
in this field is

00:52:41.760 --> 00:52:44.370
from for my early
career as a journalist,

00:52:44.370 --> 00:52:46.520
I chased action sport
athletes around mountains

00:52:46.520 --> 00:52:47.480
for five, six years.

00:52:47.480 --> 00:52:50.660
And obviously, I'm not
an action sport athlete.

00:52:50.660 --> 00:52:52.330
So I broke a lot of
bones along the way.

00:52:52.330 --> 00:52:54.790
And I would have these
year-long injuries,

00:52:54.790 --> 00:52:57.010
where I'd have 65 hairline
fractures in my leg

00:52:57.010 --> 00:52:58.710
and I didn't move for a year.

00:52:58.710 --> 00:53:01.870
And I would come back to
the sport a year later.

00:53:01.870 --> 00:53:05.140
And it was like 30 years
of evolution in a year.

00:53:05.140 --> 00:53:07.550
And my first question was,
what the hell's going on?

00:53:07.550 --> 00:53:09.530
How is this even possible?

00:53:09.530 --> 00:53:13.970
So what actually happened in
action sports, a lot of it

00:53:13.970 --> 00:53:16.520
was-- so creativity
is a flow trigger.

00:53:16.520 --> 00:53:18.200
Creativity is amplified by flow.

00:53:18.200 --> 00:53:19.960
But the actual
pattern recognition

00:53:19.960 --> 00:53:22.450
when you link
ideas together, you

00:53:22.450 --> 00:53:23.770
get a tiny squirt of dopamine.

00:53:23.770 --> 00:53:25.020
We've all had this experience.

00:53:25.020 --> 00:53:26.000
You've done a crossword puzzle.

00:53:26.000 --> 00:53:27.000
You get an answer right.

00:53:27.000 --> 00:53:29.020
That little rush of
pleasure you get afterwards,

00:53:29.020 --> 00:53:30.470
that's dopamine.

00:53:30.470 --> 00:53:32.830
Dopamine also tunes
signal-to-noise ratios,

00:53:32.830 --> 00:53:35.430
meaning it allows us
to see more patterns.

00:53:35.430 --> 00:53:38.192
So the reason you get one
crossword answer right,

00:53:38.192 --> 00:53:39.900
and then you get a
couple in a row right,

00:53:39.900 --> 00:53:42.580
it's because dopamine is
helping you see more patterns.

00:53:42.580 --> 00:53:45.210
Creativity-- and it happened
because of snowboarding.

00:53:45.210 --> 00:53:46.880
Snowboarding was a banned sport.

00:53:46.880 --> 00:53:48.650
So people started
hiking their snowboards

00:53:48.650 --> 00:53:49.510
to the top of the mountains.

00:53:49.510 --> 00:53:51.510
If you're hiking your snowboard
to the top of a mountain,

00:53:51.510 --> 00:53:53.759
you don't want to be the
fastest person to the bottom,

00:53:53.759 --> 00:53:56.180
because you just spent four
hours getting to the top.

00:53:56.180 --> 00:53:57.390
And that's stupid.

00:53:57.390 --> 00:54:00.510
So instead, it became the
most creative way down

00:54:00.510 --> 00:54:01.380
is the winner.

00:54:01.380 --> 00:54:02.740
And there's not just one winner.

00:54:02.740 --> 00:54:03.880
Everybody can win.

00:54:03.880 --> 00:54:05.962
So this was adopted.

00:54:05.962 --> 00:54:07.420
It was free riding
in snowboarding.

00:54:07.420 --> 00:54:10.040
It became free skiing,
and free surfing,

00:54:10.040 --> 00:54:11.380
and on, and on, and on.

00:54:11.380 --> 00:54:13.640
And it became about creativity.

00:54:13.640 --> 00:54:17.230
And that in combination with
the risk and the other factors

00:54:17.230 --> 00:54:20.180
just started driving
so much flow.

00:54:20.180 --> 00:54:22.820
But the other thing
that happened, in 1986

00:54:22.820 --> 00:54:24.400
we invented the VCR.

00:54:24.400 --> 00:54:26.570
And it sounds really funny.

00:54:26.570 --> 00:54:29.636
But try to learn a
dynamic action sports move

00:54:29.636 --> 00:54:31.510
from a static magazine photo.

00:54:31.510 --> 00:54:32.230
It sucks.

00:54:32.230 --> 00:54:33.250
It's really hard to do.

00:54:33.250 --> 00:54:34.666
But with the
invention of the VCR,

00:54:34.666 --> 00:54:38.656
by 1986, I think it was
50% of American homes had

00:54:38.656 --> 00:54:40.130
a VCR in it by that point.

00:54:40.130 --> 00:54:41.880
And suddenly, especially
for skaters, they

00:54:41.880 --> 00:54:43.230
were the first to notice it.

00:54:43.230 --> 00:54:44.805
You could pause and rewind.

00:54:44.805 --> 00:54:47.730
And it became this
training manual.

00:54:47.730 --> 00:54:50.790
So technology,
coupled with flow,

00:54:50.790 --> 00:54:53.880
created this massive
feedback loop that

00:54:53.880 --> 00:54:55.095
led us to where we are today.

