01:01:32.000 --> 01:01:37.610
But to answer your question,
the most famous of all flows

01:01:37.610 --> 01:01:41.080
triggers is what's known as
the challenge skills balance.

01:01:41.080 --> 01:01:44.610
So the idea here-- and you
alluded to it a second ago-- is

01:01:44.610 --> 01:01:49.200
we pay most attention-- so
every one of these flow triggers

01:01:49.200 --> 01:01:52.660
are literally just ways of
driving attention into the now.

01:01:52.660 --> 01:01:54.570
Flow follows focus.

01:01:54.570 --> 01:01:56.640
So all these triggers
are-- basically

01:01:56.640 --> 01:02:00.020
the 17 triggers that we know
of-- they're the 17 things

01:02:00.020 --> 01:02:03.820
evolution shaped your brain
to pay the most attention to.

01:02:03.820 --> 01:02:06.170
So one of them is called the
challenge skills balance.

01:02:06.170 --> 01:02:09.070
It means I pay the most
attention to the task at hand

01:02:09.070 --> 01:02:13.410
when the task at hand makes
me stretch but not snap.

01:02:13.410 --> 01:02:15.390
So you want something
that's difficult.

01:02:15.390 --> 01:02:17.497
It's beyond your
skill set but not

01:02:17.497 --> 01:02:19.330
too difficult that it's
starting to generate

01:02:19.330 --> 01:02:20.720
massive amounts of fear.

01:02:20.720 --> 01:02:22.830
It's a tricky balance to find.

01:02:22.830 --> 01:02:24.890
For example, under-performers
don't like it

01:02:24.890 --> 01:02:27.020
because you hit this
sweet spot, it's

01:02:27.020 --> 01:02:29.529
usually the point you start
to get really uncomfortable.

01:02:29.529 --> 01:02:30.570
There's no way around it.

01:02:30.570 --> 01:02:33.340
You're beyond your
comfort zone, literally.

01:02:33.340 --> 01:02:36.020
But for overachievers,
they screw up

01:02:36.020 --> 01:02:39.936
because overachievers-- so a guy
named Mihaly Csikszentmihalyi

01:02:39.936 --> 01:02:42.310
is often called the godfather
of flow-- he's a University

01:02:42.310 --> 01:02:45.466
of Chicago psychologist-- and
a Google mathematician sat

01:02:45.466 --> 01:02:46.840
down and tried to
figure out what

01:02:46.840 --> 01:02:48.520
is the exact
challenge-skills ratio.

01:02:48.520 --> 01:02:51.080
And the number, the gradient
difference they came up with,

01:02:51.080 --> 01:02:52.496
back of the envelope
calculation--

01:02:52.496 --> 01:02:53.770
this is not a real number.

01:02:53.770 --> 01:02:54.860
This is not real science.

01:02:54.860 --> 01:02:56.030
It's pretend science.

01:02:56.030 --> 01:02:57.360
But the number was 4%.

01:02:57.360 --> 01:02:59.940
So a 4% difference between
challenge and skills.

01:02:59.940 --> 01:03:04.824
What happens with really high
performers is we'll blow by 4%

01:03:04.824 --> 01:03:05.740
without even noticing.

01:03:05.740 --> 01:03:08.470
We'll take on challenge that's
10% greater, 20% greater,

01:03:08.470 --> 01:03:09.690
30% greater.

01:03:09.690 --> 01:03:12.010
Generates so much fear,
you will block yourself

01:03:12.010 --> 01:03:13.240
from a flow state.

01:03:13.240 --> 01:03:16.550
So we pay the most
attention to those things

01:03:16.550 --> 01:03:18.500
where we stretch but don't snap.

01:03:18.500 --> 01:03:20.020
They call it the flow channel.

01:03:20.020 --> 01:03:22.050
What it basically means that
there's not enough stimulation,

01:03:22.050 --> 01:03:22.570
you're bored.

01:03:22.570 --> 01:03:24.361
You're not paying a
whole lot of attention.

01:03:24.361 --> 01:03:25.980
Too much stimulation,
there's anxiety,

01:03:25.980 --> 01:03:27.140
and it'll kick you out.

01:03:27.140 --> 01:03:29.410
In between is this sweet
spot, this flow channel.

01:03:29.410 --> 01:03:32.570
And that can be applied
anywhere, obviously-- sports,

01:03:32.570 --> 01:03:34.280
